Part 1: Explain (in english) each line of the following code chunk

pattern <- "(ST|RD|ROAD)"
LeftOvers <-
  Addresses %>% 
  filter( !grepl(pattern, address),
          !grepl("\\sAPT|UNIT\\s[\\d]+$", address),
          !grepl(" BOX ", address)
          )

My answer here. 1. The variable pattern is assigned to the pattern (ST|RD|ROAD) 2. New variable LeftOvers is initialised 3. This line used the pipe operator to pass Addresses data frame as the first argument to the next function 4. The filter() function is used on the Addresses data frame in this line. It gets rid of rows where the address column fits the pattern that was set up before. The grepl() method is used to match patterns, and the! operator turns the result into the opposite of what it was. 5. This line adds another rule to the process of screening. It gets rid of rows where the address column meets the pattern sAPT|UNITs[d]+$ in a regular expression. This pattern works with addresses that end with APT or UNIT followed by a space and a number. 6. This line adds another condition to the filtering process. It removes rows where the address column contains the substring BOX .

Part 2: Implement your method on the entire Addresses data set. Explain how your code works line by line.


pattern <- "(ST|RD|ROAD)"
LeftOvers <- Addresses %>%
  filter(
    !grepl(pattern, address),
    !grepl("\\sAPT|UNIT\\s[\\d]+$", address),
    !grepl(" BOX ", address)
  )

My answer here. In this implementation, the code filters the Addresses data frame based on three conditions: street endings, APT or UNIT followed by a number, and the substring BOX . The resulting filtered addresses are stored in the LeftOvers variable.

Additional Question 2: Present your result by using ggplot to a bar chart in descending order of popularity for the street name endings you found previously.

Note: make sure your order street names according to popularity, not alphabetically.

library(ggplot2)

# Create a data frame with the street name endings and their counts
result <- data.frame(Street_Name_Ending = names(street_endings_counts),
                     Count = as.vector(street_endings_counts))

# Sort the data frame in descending order of count
result <- result[order(result$Count, decreasing = TRUE), ]

# Create the bar plot
ggplot(result, aes(x = reorder(Street_Name_Ending, -Count), y = Count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(x = "Street Name Ending", y = "Count", title = "Street Name Endings Popularity") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1)) +
  coord_flip()

Additional Question 3: Comment on any patterns you see

My answer here. The most popular ending for a street name is St, followed by Ave and Dr. Compared to other ends, these three have much higher counts. Some middle-range street name endings, like Cir and Ln, seem to be more common than others, but they still dont have as many as the top three endings.
